a33cead4-e971-58c7-963f-5ea17ba2ecc6,tg:rubgr:2181,e73_Descriptions,,id.desc,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,"[recto] Seen at Agnew's but belonging to a family at Cotton Hall, Derbigshire (Mrs. Yeats-Brown) daughter of last owner of Cotton Hall). Peasants tying Faggots (Roundel). A very good version of Marlier, p. ...[sic] The ground partly painted in brown with some dots-imitation of Bruegel. Rubens technique, but actually imitation of it, not forming an underlying layer of brown etc. Fat Man on left in red trouses, lean man on right in blush green trouses & jacket. The left man well dressed, the thin man in rags. The black cap (partly, but not ?) pointillistic. The grey jacket of the fat man and the trouses of the right man partly transparent now. so that ground now partly visible (Bruegel technique); [verso] The outlines of the figures partly drawn in dark colour, but no pentimenti. The man on the ladder with blue jacket. Apart from some rubbing in rather good condition. XIX C. frame, oak panel. On back part of Christie stencil ..SSID... still visible. Composition fits nicely into roundel: originally intented for such. The Birmingham rectangular version for this reason alone would speaks against copy after the lost original. Not in Marlier.",descriptive note,Nederlands,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,

column4: <content>[recto] Seen at Agnew's but belonging to a family at Cotton Hall, Derbigshire (Mrs. Yeats-Brown) daughter of last owner of Cotton Hall). Peasants tying Faggots (Roundel). A very good version of Marlier, p. ...[sic] The ground partly painted in brown with some dots-imitation of Bruegel. Rubens technique, but actually imitation of it, not forming an underlying layer of brown etc. Fat Man on left in red trouses, lean man on right in blush green trouses & jacket. The left man well dressed, the thin man in rags. The black cap (partly, but not ?) pointillistic. The grey jacket of the fat man and the trouses of the right man partly transparent now. so that ground now partly visible (Bruegel technique); [verso] The outlines of the figures partly drawn in dark colour, but no pentimenti. The man on the ladder with blue jacket. Apart from some rubbing in rather good condition. XIX C. frame, oak panel. On back part of Christie stencil ..SSID... still visible. Composition fits nicely into roundel: originally intented for such. The Birmingham rectangular version for this reason alone would speaks against copy after the lost original. Not in Marlier.</content>
